      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>5 threads, <a href=journal.html?user=93075&start=0>1</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></form><ul><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=101657281774747></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f101657281774747><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93075&mid=101657281774747>St. Patty's Day or The Ides of March?</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93075&mid=101657281774747#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id= >Releaux</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Mar 19th 4:23 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, I'm taking advantage of today's patch-driven downtime to add another entry to my journal. This is a major patch that will change the way many of us play the game. What remains to be seen is whether this patch will be a St. Patty's Day Celebration or a victim of the Ides of March...<br><br>From my point of view, there aren't many things to dislike about this patch unless you're one of the Snobby EQ Veterans I griped about a couple of entries ago. While there is a small part of me that wants others to suffer through 34 levels of staring at a spellbook (especially since I *just* got to level 35 about a week ago), the more rational side of me knows that this was just a pain that nobody should suffer through.<br><br>I've read several well-communicated opinions on both sides of the experience debate, and while there may be an increase in high-level characters without all of the skills they need, I don't think it's going to be the massive problem some people are gnashing their teeth over.<br><br>Why? Well, there might be one or two times when someone without crowd control skills leads to the death of their party, but EQ's inherent Darwinism will take care of that. Players without appropriate skills will either learn those skills, or they will quickly develop a reputation and not get in any more groups.<br><br>There are two reasons I'm excited about these changes:<br><br>1. It will make it much easier for me to play another character. I have a limited amount of time to play - I can't spend 8 hours a day getting my toons up to the 50s... it's taken me nearly a year to get my primary up to 36. <br><br>The randomized skinner box model is still there, but making it less frustrating can only make things better, in my opinion, for both the players *and* Verant. I'll be happier because the game is slightly easier and I'm more able to enjoy other classes more readily, and Verant will profit because I'll be more likely to stay subscribed so I can get that mage or bard leveled up as well...<br><br>2. By removing some of the artificial game-lengthening aspects, Verant has actually (to my surprise) made the game more enjoyable for the majority of players instead of trying to push some strange philosophy/dogma or spurious rationale to make the game harder and longer (thus increasing the amount of time people are likely to subscribe).<br><br>For whatever reason (change in management, economic forces), Verant seems to be making fundamental changes in the game that nearly everyone wanted. I hope that this signals a new customer-satisfaction focus from Verant. They have a fantastic product that I love to play, I'm even more inclined to stay subscribed if they treat me nicely as well.<br><br>There are a few things that I disagree with in the changes - I think Clerics should still be the primary resurrection artists... there aren't many other reasons to suffer through the boredom that is a Cleric's life.<br><br>There was also one change that didn't make it in, that I thought should have been included. Since Luclin came out, the Wizard and Druid porting skills (and subsequent income potential) dropped. It's my opinion that the availability of various port spells should be changed. West Commons should now be one of the first port spells these classes receive, and Toxx forest one of the last. This way, there would still be an in-demand income-producing service that wizzies and dr00ds could provide during those levels when you really need money to equip yourself for the higher levels in the game.<br><br>Perhaps that will be looked at in a future patch. I hope so. I don't have a wizard or a druid, but I feel for those who do. At the same time, however, the ability to port quickly through Luclin made the game *incredibly* more enjoyable for me.<br><br>One final comment (and this one is definitely a biased one), I think that the cost for components for spells like Summon Corpse should be in line with the amount of money people are willing to pay for the service, especially for the level that a spell becomes available.<br><br>Lesser Summon Corpse is now available to low level necromancers and Summon Corpse is now available at Level 39. Yet according to the databases I've seen, the cost of a coffin is still very high. <br><br>If a coffin costs 100pp, a necromancer really needs to charge at least 130 to 150 to make a decent profit covering not only the high cost of the component, but to make up for the relative popularity of the service. Even in the high 30s and low to mid 40s, 150pp to summon a corpse is pretty steep, and most people will ask the necro to simply track the corpse instead (if they don't just go find it themselves).<br><br>I've never been offered (nor have I asked) for a donation for tracking a corpse... it's just not something that people attach a value to unless their corpse is about to rot along with all their gear. But that is rarely the case.<br><br>Everyone has needed to get to the commons quickly at some point, and I still see lots of shouts for ports. I've never *ever* seen a shout for someone to summon a corpse. If the component cost me 20pp and I could charge 25 or 30pp (in line with other time-saving services like ports), then I think many more people would find the service advantageous.<br><br>I don't know the details on the difference between Lesser Summon Corpse and Summon Corpse, nor do I know if there's an additional spell in the line, but the main point I'm trying to make is that when components are prohibitively expensive, nobody will ask for the service.<br>&nbsp;<br>Bene Moriore!<br>Ynar - Necromancer of the 8th Circle, Zebuxoruk</td></tr>
