<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=10146940611124></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f10146940611124><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=93075&mid=10146940611124>Legends - Timeless or Moldy?</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=93075&mid=10146940611124#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93075><span id= >Releaux</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Feb 25th 10:28 PM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Note: I had just finished penning this latest diatribe when I read another interview on the Legends server... I'll leave my original post as is, but will append additional thoughts at the end.<br><br><br><br>So... Verant has now come out with Everquest Legends - a premium service at a very premium price. I won't bother to make the business school case for this product. I think it makes sense for Verant and a small portion of EQ players, and frankly, it looks like pretty cool.<br><br>In fact, it looks like what I thought Everquest was going to be when I first subscribed last summer.<br><br>First, the positives. <br><br>* Lots of events<br>* A truly dynamic world where what you do might actually have an impact<br>* Lower server populations<br>* (Presumably) fewer low-quality players (the kind that train you, or still can't effectively group despite having a level 40 toon, etc.)<br><br>That last one is a double-edged two-handed slash weapon, though. I've found that there are two types of EQ players that annoy me to no end. First, &quot;The n00b&quot; (as opposed to newbie) who doesn't care about the game, doesn't want to care about the game, and generally only cares about leveling, phat lewt, and going to Lake of Ill Manners to start arguments (&quot;What's the best class?&quot;).<br><br>Secondly, and perhaps controversially, is the Snobby EQ Veteran. This person is, in my mind, the same person as Comic Book Guy from The Simpsons. (&quot;Worst Zone Patch Ever.&quot;) They have 7 characters at level 60, 12 more in the 50s, and are so damn elitist that you just want to slap them. These are the same people who frequently get their knickers in a twist when you inspect &quot;without permission&quot; (THE HORROR!!!). I won't bring that debate up here except to say that 1. I don't care if you inspect me - Verant put that there because they couldn't accomplish the same thing in the graphics engine and 2. If you do care, just turn off the stupid message! It's very easy to do.<br><br>(Note that not all people who are offended by inspection are Snobby EQ Veterans, but nearly all Snobby EQ Veterans are offended by inspection.)<br><br>Unfortunately, it's my suspicion that there will be a higher-than-normal concentration of these so-called &quot;serious&quot; players on the Legends servers, and that's almost enough by itself to keep me on Zebuxoruk.<br><br>Almost, but not quite. I would gladly ignore the elite and sign up for legends were it not for its one overwhelming drawback:<br><br>It costs $40 a month!<br><br>Now, I'm just a simple Necromancer and not too good at math, but I believe that adds up to $480 a year! I thought $120 was steep! Don't get me wrong, EQ is still a pretty good bargain when it comes to cost/time. I play a lot of EQ and when you break it down on a per hour basis, I think I get my money's worth.<br><br>But I have yet to see a GM event that's worth an extra $30 per month. These events typically turn whatever zone they afflict into a madhouse of chaotic shouts, name calling, flames, and generally poor behavior. It's my feeling that this is because events have little focus, even less back-story, and almost no information provided ahead of time to allow people to get into the event and play the storyline out. Thus we are treated to:<br><br>&quot;Is the event starting&quot;<br>&quot;About to.&quot;<br>&quot;I JUST KILLED A HAIRY PHLEGMBALL!!!&quot;<br>&quot;WHAT'D IT DROP?????&quot;<br>&quot;DAMN NEAR KILLED ME!!!&quot;<br>&quot;Don't kill the Voracious Nosehair - it ends the event!!!&quot;<br>&quot;WHAT'D IT DROP????????????&quot;<br>&quot;Umm.... Bracer of Mucus&quot;<br>&quot;KEWL! STATS???&quot;<br>&quot;Ummmm.... +5 Save vs. Disease and 40AC&quot;<br>&quot;OMFG!!! I WANT ONE!!!!!:<br>&quot;ME TOO!&quot;<br>&quot;ME TOO!&quot;<br>&quot;Taking bids on bracer. I'll give loc to highest bid... hurry, it's rotting!&quot;<br>&quot;d00d - ur a l00ser... let everyone take their turn&quot;<br>&quot;shut up&quot;<br>&quot;no you shut up&quot;<br>&quot;I'm tracking a Voracious Nosehair&quot;<br>&quot;DON'T KILL IT!!!&quot;<br>&quot;DUDE! Don't kill it!!! It ends the event!!!!!&quot;<br>&quot;Donating 200pp for loc of a Bracer of Mucus!&quot;<br>&quot;Killing a Voracious Nosehair&quot;<br>&quot;NOOOOO!!!!&quot;<br>&quot;You're a jerk!&quot;<br>&quot;shut up&quot;<br>&quot;no YOU shut up&quot;<br>&quot;EVERYBODY SHUT UP!&quot;<br>&quot;Voracious Nosehair is dead!&quot;<br>&quot;You're a jerk. BTW, what'd it drop?&quot;<br>&quot;when does the event start up again?????&quot;<br><br><br>And on... and on... and on... All from an event that could have been cool had we just known that an evil wizard had miscast a spell and given life to his sinus infection. But the events become less about the story, and more about the lewt - leading to an immediate zone population of 150+ (when it's normally 20) consisting mostly of guild folks with access to a wizard or druid that can port them there.<br><br>So what's the alternative? Given the limitations of the game and EQ?s architecture, there aren't a lot. I always dreamed, however, of a scenario something like this:<br><br>I'm in a group that is working well together. Maybe we've grouped for the first time, maybe we're a regular party, but we're having a good time together and wasting just about everything we come across. Somewhere, the GM is watching and identifies us as a group that works well together. The event begins when a wandering (GM) character approaches our group and begs for assistance - a band of orcs has abducted his sister. <br><br>Or a powerful mage appears in a thunderclap and tells us that she has rewards beyond imagination for all, but we must prove ourselves worthy first and proceeds to send us on a quest. Even better, she hires us to accompany her at 10pp a day plus whatever loot we can carry and then we all go on the quest together. It wouldn't be too difficult to hide quests of this sort so that they could only be started with the pass-phrase given by the GM. Heck, most people have a hard enough time finding real EQ quests without searching one of the fine web sites like Allakhazam (worth every cent of the premium fee, by the way) or shouting to an entire zone to find out what a Sarnak War Braid is used for...<br><br>Now maybe if the events were *always* going on, they wouldn't have quite the draw that they normally do and behaviors would change. I hope that's the case for Legends servers, because I'd be pretty ticked off to pay extra for the dubious privilege of living in a constant GM event atmosphere as it exists on Zebuxoruk<br><br>I've read the interviews about Legends and I don't doubt that $40/month is indeed the magic number that Verant needs to charge to run the servers, pay for bandwidth, pay salaries, make Legends a self-sufficient cost/profit center. But it's about $20-25 more than I'm willing to pay.<br><br>Perhaps it's my loss. Perhaps I'm not hardcore enough. But so be it - for now, I'll stay on Zebuxoruk and wreak my havoc and terror there. There may never be a spell named &quot;Ynar's Acid Tongue,&quot; but heck... enough people on Zebux already know that Ynar has an acid tongue!<br><br><br>APPENDIX<br><br>Ok, I just finished reading another interview about the legends server, this time with one of the GMs. It appears that many of my concerns are actually being addressed on the Legends server (and I can count on one hand the number of times that Verant and I actually thought similarly on an issue).<br><br>There are two quotes of note:<br><br>Q: How will you prevent people flocking to zones for quest loot?<br><br>A: One of the things you will see is a change in Focus whereby not all quests will be obvious and large-scale. Many will be small group based quests that will not get the attention of entire guilds of people.<br><br><br>Very nice! This is exactly what I was talking about. And:<br><br><br>Q: Will GM's contact me when events are on?<br><br>A: Not directly no. But if you are in a group don't be surprised if one day some strange NPC comes up and starts interacting with your party. You can then choose to participate or not.<br><br><br>It's almost like they were reading my mind. Now if only they could drop the price by $15-20, I'd be hard-pressed not to upgrade. Ultimately, though, I don't play enough to slog through trying to level another necromancer. I've been playing since last June and have only reached 33 with Ynar (34 any day now). And I'd hate to transfer Ynar because I've made so many great friends. So maybe someday I'll move to legends.<br><br>But not today.<br><br><br><br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Mon Feb 25 22:37:57 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br>Bene Moriore!<br>Ynar - Necromancer of the 8th Circle, Zebuxoruk</td></tr>
